(909, '{"subject":"  posted a comment","message":{"comments":"Hi Lawrence, thanks for conitctang Plugin Dynamo support. I''ll answer your questions numbered as you asked them:1. Yes, only images that are using in your post are uploaded to your server. The process Buzz goes through to capture images is, it scans the feed items looks for all image url''s once it has them it associates each image with the post data for the feed, if more feeds are found than you want in your post, it randomly filters them and once it has the final ones to use in the post, it goes through and add it to the post and saves the image locally.2.In the settings page I believe there''s a setting for max image height and max image width, this is for the imported images.3. They will still work, but images won''t show up and in some browsers people will see the image wont load box i.e. chrome I believe does this.4. You use to be able to do this, but it caused alot of confusion, so now its for the whole campaign as you said it all or nothing.If there''s anything else you would like to know just let us know.Thanks,Plugin Dynamo Support"}}', '2014-02-11 20:38:38', '1'),
(910, '{"subject":"  posted a comment","message":{"comments":"Hi John, thanks for cotticnang Plugin Dynamo Support.Unfortunately there is no way to increase\\/decrease the check email time limit. It is set to every 15 minutes though and fires off through a WordPress cron job. But your hick up might be coming from the fact that WordPress cron jobs don''t work exactly like a regular server cron job. Every time an action happens on your site, someone lands on any page, you log in as admin, you browse admin pages your WordPress install fires off the cron, and scans through at what job''s are set to run at that time, if no jobs are set to run, nothing happens. If there are jobs it runs them.So that''s why there''s a little bit of give and take on the time. No action on the site = cron doesn''t fire to retrieve emails.You can however manually retrieve the emails by visiting settings > email settings this will force a check.Or you can edit the time limit yourself in the code, by editing line #427 Currently:  interval'' => 900, to a desired time you want (in seconds) 900\\/60 = 15 minutes.5 minutes would be 300If you change it this way, de-activate the Plugin and re-activate it and the new schedule time should be in the cron job for you. Just be sure to go back and re-edit the line should you ever update the Plugin.Thanks,Plugin Dynamo Support"}}', '2014-02-11 20:42:19', '1'),
