(995, '{"subject":"  posted a comment","message":{"comments":"Thanks for your comments and aaylws-insightful perspective. Market entry costs depend on the market geographic size, the market niche size, the mode of entry, the types of marketing promotion needed, country-specific setup costs and the mode of product\\/service delivery. Most entrepreneurs I talk to and work with typically choose to start off small in their internationalization. They find a good local partner who can represent their products in-country in exchange for either representation in our country or else a steep commission fee per item sold. This entry mode is the least cost and least risk. Many would argue that it is the least reward too. Typically the evolution I''ve seen when I company realizes that they can compete profitably in a market is to move from partners\\/representatives\\/licensees to eventually setting up a local sales office. If a partnership proves to be highly fruitful in more than just sales, then it may be advantageous to eventually either set up a joint venture entity, try to acquire the partner or set up a greenfield investment in-country on your own. There are lots of options with different price tags. The range can easily be from US$10,000 to US$10 million. If any entrepreneurial companies need weighing entry options and budgeting for international markets, this is a major part of what my company does for small and medium-sized companies."}}', '2014-02-12 15:24:02', '1'),
